{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (also known as the Manusmṛti or Laws of Manu) chapter 1 specifies the duration of the Kṛta Yuga (also spelled Kr̥ta or Krita Yuga) in divine years as follows:**\n\n- The main period of the Kṛta Yuga is **4,000 years**.[^1]\n- It is preceded by a **sandhyā** (twilight or transitional period) of **400 years** and followed by another **400 years**.[^1]\n\nThis gives a **total duration of 4,800 divine years** for the full Kṛta Yuga (including twilights).[^1][^2]\n\nThe text then describes the **ratio** of durations across the four yugas (Kṛta, Tretā, Dvāpara, and Kali), where the \"thousands and hundreds\" diminish successively by one for each subsequent yuga (e.g., Tretā: 3,000 + 300 + 300 = 3,600; Dvāpara: 2,000 + 200 + 200 = 2,400; Kali: 1,000 + 100 + 100 = 1,200). The four yugas together total **12,000 divine years** (a \"mahāyuga\" or age of the gods), establishing the classic **4:3:2:1 ratio** for their durations.[^1][^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 1*, [Mn_1.69](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-a2767c).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, *Chapter 1*, [Mn_1.70-71](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-85c454).",
